In .NET MAUI, use `ConfigureLifecycleEvents` in `MauiProgram.cs`:

```csharp
using Microsoft.Maui.LifecycleEvents;

public static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()
{
    var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();
    builder.UseMauiApp<App>();

    builder.ConfigureLifecycleEvents(events =>
    {
#if ANDROID
        events.AddAndroid(android => android
            .OnPause(activity =>
            {
                // App is partially obscured
            })
            .OnStop(activity =>
            {
                // App is no longer visible
            }));
#elif IOS
        events.AddiOS(ios => ios
            .DidEnterBackground(application =>
            {
                // App moved to background
            }));
#endif
    });

    return builder.Build();
}
```

**Key points:**
- Use `#if ANDROID` / `#elif IOS` preprocessor directives to keep platform code separated.
- Android provides `OnPause`, `OnStop`, `OnResume`, `OnStart`, `OnDestroy`, etc.
- iOS provides `DidEnterBackground`, `WillEnterForeground`, `WillTerminate`, etc.
- The delegates receive the platform-native object (`Activity` on Android, `UIApplication` on iOS).
